        "impacts": "Events have highlighted vulnerable zones in the city - in Selly Oak, Witton and Northfield; for large scale events (10,000 residents). The West Midlands Combined Authority's Summary of Climate Change Impacts highlights several direct risks to Birmingham and its citizens, including the increased risk of fires, floods and damage to property and infrastructure. The impact of flooding alone is significant, with the current annual cost of flood damage across the UK exceeding \u00a3700m, and the repairs for a flooded home costing \u00a330,000 on average. More frequent localised events, continue to occur across the city through local storm events. The two most significant impacts are over-heating and flood risk. We have now mapped those impacts on vulnerable communities. Public Health has an Emergency Heat Plan; and our Flood Risk team work with the Environment Agency & local water companies for both flood risk and drought; both through our Civil Contingencies Plan. A further impact of urban heat can also be that of air quality peaks; we now have a Ward based Tool that again is able to map both the physical risk and the human impact.",
