    "q1_3": {
      "oversightProcesses": "Climate-related responsibilities are assigned to management-level positions in the government|Relevant departments, committees and/or subcommittees are informed by management about climate-related issues|Climate-related responsibilities are assigned to a committee(s) or a subcommittee(s) in the government|Climate-related issues are considered by the government when undertaking plans and/or strategies|Climate-related issues are considered by the government when undertaking budgeting and/or major capital expenditures|Council (or equivalent) is informed by relevant departments, committees and/or subcommittees about climate-related issues",
      "oversightDetails": "Cambridgeshire County Council does not have complete oversight of climate relates issues. While we are able to set our own strategy and policy, and undertake actions, these are only those within our remit as an upper tier authority. Operating across the region we also have a variety of other public sector organisations who all, largely independently, have their own political positions and policies on the environment. These include: Fenland District Council, Huntingdonshire District Council, Cambridge City Council, South Cambridgeshire District Council, East Cambridgeshire District Council, Cambridgeshire and Peterborough Combined Authority, Police Service, Fire Service and the NHS amongst others. While we coordinate action where possible, we have little influence over the decisions and actions taken by these organisations, and cannot speak to functions that are their responsibility to deliver. For example, Government (DEFRA) places responsibly for air quality with the district councils. We can report some of that information here, but ultimately they have the statutory responsibility on this topic and therefore the actions are primarily developed, delivered and monitored by them. ",
      "masterPlanningImpact": "Development planning is primarily co-ordinated by the City and District Councils. Climate-related issues have certainly impacted this, for example in the transition to low carbon energy generation, housing and transport. ",
      "financialPlanningImpact": "The County Council has committed expenditure towards implementing its Net Zero programme and resourcing plan. The carbon impacts are now considered in capital projects and other decisions. ",
      "transitionRisks": "Risk of unequal access to low carbon technologies due to share of population in rural areas and in deprived areas. "
    },
    "q1_4": {
      "assessesOpportunities": "Yes, wider opportunities/benefits are assessed for some climate actions",
      "assessmentMethod": "Wider opportunities/benefits are quantitatively assessed|Wider opportunities/benefits are considered at the action planning stage|Wider opportunities/benefits are considered at the action implementation stage|Wider opportunities/benefits are qualitatively assessed",
      "opportunitiesIdentified": "We are taking steps to understand at a macro-level the benefits climate action can bring our region and are beginning to try and quantify these benefits via Triple Bottom Line accounting approaches. We are also assessing wider co-benefits for some actions, for example, saving money and addressing fuel poverty through increasing energy efficiency. ",
      "equitableDistribution": "Yes, the jurisdiction is designing or implementing climate actions that address the needs of frontline communities most impacted by climate change",
      "quantifiesEquity": "There is not one single approach to this, but a variety of climate actions that are quantified in different ways. ",
      "equityEvidence": "A just transition is a key policy area for Cambridgeshire County Council and we are integrating equity and inclusivity into our decision making. Some of this is also picked up via our legal duties around equality, inclusion and diversity following the Equality Act. "
    },
