        "impacts": "Everyone is at risk of harm from increasing temperatures and extreme heat events. Some groups are able to protect themselves better than others, and some groups will face multiple increased risks.\\nProperties that are prone to overheating such as top-floor flats, poorly ventilated homes, urban residences, south-facing properties, those with dormers, large windows, conservatories, smaller properties, overcrowded or temporary accommodations, and bungalows or ground-floor bedrooms\u2014pose extra risks, especially for individuals with limited financial means to secure cooling measures. Vulnerable people include older adults, very young children, pregnant women, those with chronic health conditions or on medications affecting heat regulation, individuals already ill or dehydrated, people facing mental health or substance issues, and those with learning disabilities or living alone, along with outdoor workers and manual labourers are also at higher levels of risk. Some people will be exposed to multiple risk factors. \\n\\nExtreme heat poses a significant hazard to vulnerable populations and critical sectors, amplifying existing inequalities and straining infrastructure. Elderly individuals, children, outdoor workers, and those with pre-existing health conditions are particularly at risk, as prolonged exposure can lead to heatstroke, dehydration, and even death. Low-income communities often lack access to cooling systems or green spaces, compounding their vulnerability. Key sectors such as agriculture, construction, and energy face disruptions\u2014crop yields decline, productivity drops, and power grids are pushed to their limits by surging demand. As climate change intensifies, these hazards are becoming more frequent and severe, demanding urgent adaptation strategies and targeted support to protect those most at risk.\\n\\n",
