        "hazard": "Drought",
        "vulnerableGroups": "Indigenous peoples|Frontline workers|Vulnerable health groups|Outdoor workers|Elderly|Children and youth|Women and girls|Low-income households|Marginalized/minority communities",
        "sectorsExposed": "Construction|Agriculture|Human health and social work activities|Transportation and storage|Forestry|Manufacturing|Water supply|Education|Electricity, gas, steam and air conditioning supply|Sewerage, waste management and remediation activities|Waste management|Administrative and support service activities|Fishing|Wholesale and retail trade; repair of motor vehicles and motorcycles|Mining and quarrying|Conservation",
        "impacts": "\\nDrought presents a growing hazard to vulnerable populations and key sectors within the Bradford District, particularly as climate change drives hotter, drier summers. Communities already facing social and health inequalities\u2014such as older adults, young children, and those with chronic conditions\u2014are disproportionately affected by water scarcity, heat stress, and reduced access to hydration and hygiene. Sectors like agriculture, healthcare, and education also feel the strain, with farmers facing crop failures and mental health challenges, while schools and care facilities must adapt to rising temperatures and limited water supply. In 2022 and 2025, Yorkshire officially entered drought conditions, prompting urgent calls for water conservation across Bradford. Local authorities and residents are now encouraged to adopt sustainable water practices, improve infrastructure resilience, and prepare for more frequent dry spells as part of the district's climate adaptation strategy.\\n\\nAll water companies are required by the Government to produce a drought plan which sets out triggers and actions to maintain water supplies to customers in the event of a prolonged period of exceptionally low rainfall.\\n\\nBelow is the link to Yorkshire Water Drought Plan:\\n\\nhttps://www.yorkshirewater.com/about-us/our-vision-and-plans/resources/drought-plan/",
