        "hazard": "Biodiversity loss",
        "vulnerableGroups": "Indigenous peoples|Vulnerable health groups|Children and youth|Elderly|Frontline workers|Low-income households|Outdoor workers|Women and girls|Marginalized/minority communities",
        "sectorsExposed": "Human health and social work activities|Water supply|Agriculture|Conservation|Sewerage, waste management and remediation activities|Waste management|Fishing|Forestry",
        "impacts": "Biodiversity loss in the Bradford District poses serious challenges for vulnerable populations and key sectors, particularly in urban and deprived communities with limited access to green spaces. As habitats degrade and species decline\u2014from wildflowers and pollinators to birds and aquatic life\u2014ecosystem services such as clean air, water regulation, and mental health benefits are diminished. This disproportionately affects older adults, children, and those with health conditions who rely on nearby nature for wellbeing and respite. Sectors like healthcare, education, and our nature based tourism also suffer, with fewer opportunities for outdoor learning, therapeutic activities, and nature-based recreation. Bradford Council has declared a biodiversity emergency and is working to make neighbourhoods more nature-friendly, recognising that environmental harm and lack of access to biodiversity are matters of social justice. Without urgent action, the district risks losing not only its ecological richness but also the resilience and wellbeing of its most vulnerable residents. \\n\\nIn 2025 Bradford Council and partners succeeded in ensuring the protection of many green and bio diverse parts of the district by gaining the status of a new National Nature Reserve and eight additional local reserve sites. See the link below for more information. \\n\\nhttps://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/cewdvk4x2qyo",
