        "sectorsExposed": "Manufacturing|Water supply|Conservation|Human health and social work activities",
        "impacts": "Although currently relatively rare, climate projections suggest that Manchester will face increased risks of drought in the future due to changing precipitation patterns and higher temperatures. Droughts could lead to water shortages, impacting both domestic supply and critical infrastructure. Reduced water availability could particularly affect vulnerable groups (such as those who are deprived, health-impaired, young, or elderly) who may lack resources to cope with water scarcity. Prolonged drought periods could affect areas where these groups are concentrated, worsening inequalities.\\n\\nAs part of the Greater Manchester (GM) Critical Infrastructure Risk Assessment, using projected climate change scenarios (developed under the EcoCities project: https://resin-cities.eu/fileadmin/user_upload/Resources/City_report_GM/GMCCRA_report_final.pdf) for a 2050's high GHG emissions scenario, the implications of prolonged droughts could be significant, particularly for public health. Vulnerable populations are likely to face higher exposure to water scarcity, affecting their ability to maintain hygiene, access clean drinking water, and manage health conditions. Drought could also lead to food price increases, disproportionately affecting those already at socio-economic disadvantage.\\n\\nDrought also poses a threat to the functionality of urban infrastructure and green spaces in Manchester. Water restrictions could impact the city's green spaces, reducing their cooling effects and increasing the urban heat island effect. Moreover, a decline in water quality due to lower river flows could lead to increased treatment costs and health risks. The implications are potentially severe for both human health and economic stability, particularly if drought conditions persist or become more frequent.",
