        "impacts": "Climate projections indicate that winters in Manchester are expected to become generally warmer. According to UKCP 2018, by the end of the century, snowfall is likely to be rare and only occur on higher ground. However, short to medium-term cold snaps and occasional snowfall remain possible. The primary impacts are:\\n\\nHuman Health: Vulnerable populations, including the elderly, those in fuel poverty, and the homeless, face increased health risks. Manchester has an extreme cold weather plan to protect these residents.\\n\\nInfrastructure: Warmer winters could still lead to infrastructure challenges, including disruptions to transport networks, damage to water and drainage pipes, and issues with power lines due to snow and ice. Improved cross-sector collaboration and adaptation planning aim to enhance resilience.\\n\\nTransport: There may be disruptions to transport services, including potential airport and road closures.\\n\\nPublic Services: Cold weather can impact public services, leading to potential school closures, disruptions in health services, and interruptions in council services.\\n\\nEconomic Impact: Business and infrastructure disruptions could result in significant economic consequences.",
