        "description": "The Commercial Retrofit City Challenge was started in 2022, convened by Manchester Climate Change Partnership, led by Bruntwood with the task to propose a high level strategy for increasing the number of commercial retrofit works taking place across the Greater Manchester Combined Authority (GMCA)Project scope In scope \u25cfOffice, retail, leisure, logistics (Planning use classes E, B8 & C1)\u25cfCovering regulated loads only (heating, cooling, ventilation, hot water, lighting etc) Out of scope \u25cfResidential, education, public sector, industrial, health (Planning use classes F1, F2, B2, C2 & C2A)\u25cfUnregulated loads (plug in equipment, IT loads, lifts etc)Project aims \u25cfIncrease the number of commercial retrofit projects taking place and in the pipeline across GMCA \u25cfIncrease the number of buildings in Manchester that are highly energy efficient, in line with future NZC standards and aligned to e.g. NABERS, EPC etc.\u25cfIncrease the number of owners and developers choosing to retrofit their commercial assets \u25cfMake high efficiency commercial buildings more attractive to occupiers, tenants, investors etc \u25cfHelp make retrofit a viable business decision for businesses in the city \u25cfIncentivise commercial retrofit \u25cfShowcase the city as a place for change in the retrofit space \u25cfUnderstand how to link into statutory approvals eg Planning, Building Regulations etc The report is expected to be published in autumn 2024 and then work will start on launching a retrofit initiative across Manchester",
