        "comment": "Manchester City Council (MCC) engages with multiple levels of government to shape and deliver climate action, ensuring local priorities are reflected in regional, national, and international decision-making. Through these engagements, Manchester ensures that climate action is evidence-based, aligned across governance levels, and responsive to local vulnerabilities, while contributing to regional, national, and international resilience planning.\\nRegional engagement\\nMCC works closely with the Greater Manchester Combined Authority (GMCA), contributing to the Climate Risk Assessment. This assessment maps climate hazards, vulnerable communities, and critical assets, supporting targeted resilience planning across Greater Manchester and enabling Manchester to prioritise action where it is needed most. The framework has directly informed the GMCA Five-Year Environment Plan 2024-29 and guides regional investment in adaptation and mitigation measures.https://www.greatermanchester-ca.gov.uk/what-we-do/environment/natural-environment/climate-change-risk-assessment/\\nhttps://storymaps.arcgis.com/collections/cba96b0e26f64db0afb244af055a747a \\nNational engagement\\nManchester participates in national initiatives such as the Climate Change Committee's Urban Heat Project steering group, helping to shape the upcoming CCRA4. City representatives from MCC, MHCLG, and DEFRA contributed to the development of Manchester's forthcoming Adaptation Plan. In December 2024, MCC submitted its Adaptation Reporting Power (ARP) report to DEFRA as part of a 35-authority pilot trial.\\nInternational and partnership engagement\\nMCC and GMCA collaborate with partners including the Greater London Authority through programmes such as Pathways to Resilience, sharing insights and influencing policy and best practice across cities. GMCA's climate risk mapping also informs engagement with other stakeholders and EU policy initiatives, reinforcing Manchester's voice in broader climate resilience discussions.\\n"
