        "sectorsExposed": "Forestry|Conservation",
        "impacts": "Tree/shrub cover reduce extreme temperatures in built up areas, without this the more vulnerable population groups will suffer especially those who live in areas without any/small gardens. Green areas also enable carbon capture, reduce flooding and mass movement, improves air quality, increase open green space, improve health and wellbeing, increase biodiversity, and create enhanced active travel networks, new green jobs, skills and volunteering opportunities. This will have a particular impact on marginalised and minority groups according to as national UK data people of BAME background are more than twice as likely as a white person to live within England's most green space-deprived neighbourhoods. Consequently, further green space decline will exacerbate these impacts further. Evidence has show substantial health benefits of quality green (and blue) spaces, parks, corridors and neighbourhoods. Consequently, the loss of green space will have result in worse health outcomes for children, elderly and those already experiencing poor health. Mental health and green space are also closely linked, making the loss of green space detrimental to those at risk of poor mental health outcomes. The lack of green spaces and tree cover will drastically impact conservation and forestry sectors, with the sectors being intrinsically linked to the preservation of these spaces. City of York Council utilise the Tree Equity Tool to monitor the distribution of tree cover. Tree Equity Score UK is a map-based application that was created to help address disparities in urban tree distribution by identifying the areas in greatest need of people-focused investment in trees. Urban communities require trees as essential infrastructure to support public health and climate resilience. \\n\\nLoss of Green Space and Forestry for the Conservation sector will have a major impact, with loss of habitat connectivity/habitat fragmentation widely regarded as one of the leading contributors to biodiversity decline worldwide. \\n",
