        "impacts": "Risks to occupational health from extreme heat. Individuals working under heat stress are more likely to experience physiological heat strain and heat-related illness, and exertional heat stroke and death. They further consider that there can be impacts on recreation, either from discouraging people from undertaking outdoor activities or from people suffering heat-induced illness as a result of over-exposure. Heat, in particular, has been consistently associated with aggression and conflict and correlate with increased rates of suicide and of hospitalization for mental illness. Heat waves and associated heat risks including fire are likely to increase over Cornwall throughout the century potentially reaching levels currently associated with areas of Central and Southern Europe towards the end of the century. \\n\\nMarine heatwaves are more extensive with an increase in frequency, severity and length impacting on coastal waters and ecology. as well as activities such as fishing. Older people are more likely to be affected by heat stress, as they are more likely to have health conditions that make them more susceptible to heat, such as heart disease, stroke, and respiratory problems. \\n\\nChildren are also more vulnerable to heat stress, as their bodies are still developing and they may not be able to regulate their body temperature as well as adults.\\n\\nPeople with chronic health conditions, such as heart disease, stroke, respiratory problems, and diabetes, are also more vulnerable to heat stress.\\n\\nPeople who work outdoors, such as construction workers, farmers, and delivery drivers, are also more vulnerable to heat stress.\\n\\nPeople who live in poverty are more likely to live in overcrowded housing, which can make it difficult to stay cool. They may also have less access to air conditioning or fans.",
