        "focusAreas": "Ecosystem restoration|Adaptation|Emissions reduction|Inclusive climate action and/or equity|Education|Transport (Mobility)|Natural environment|Resilience",
        "description": "Access to nature & travel. We are promoting inclusive active travel to our communities and have secured almost 50M from Government to improve public transport links in Cornwall through the Mid Cornwall Metro project (total project cost \u00a356.8m). https://midcornwallmetro.com/\\n\\nThrough the Saints Trails project we have created 13km of trails for cyclists, walkers and equestrian users. This is mainly off-road to enable safer journeys for commuters and leisure users. Project funding of \u00a320m came from National Highways, the European Regional Development Fund, Local Transport Plan funding and Cornwall Council. https://www.cornwall.gov.uk/transport-parking-and-streets/sustainable-transport/active-travel-walking-and-cycling/saints-trails/\\n\\nSt Ives and Hayle Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plan - Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plans (LCWIP) have been developed by the Department for Transport (DfT) for local and regional authorities to take a strategic approach in improving walking and cycling infrastructure and encourage a shift away from motorised vehicles. The three key outputs of an LCWIP are a network plan for walking and cycling, which identifies preferred routes and core zones; a prioritised programme of infrastructure improvements for future investment; and a report which sets out the underlying analysis carried out and provides a narrative which supports the identified improvements and network. An LCWIP is being developed for St Ives and Hayle and views on opportunities for improving cycling and walking have been sought from residents. https://letstalk.cornwall.gov.uk/stives-hayle-lcwip\\n\\nWe have partnered with Beryl Bikes to deliver public e-bike hire in 4 locations across Cornwall (Penzance, Truro, Falmouth/Penryn and Newquay). Since the scheme started in July 2022 they have been ridden almost 1,000,000km, 400,000 rides have been taken and 35 tonnes of carbon have been saved. \\n\\nWe continue to promote Cornwall and the Isles of Scilly as a destination for sustainable eco-tourism. \\n\\nWe have delivered the Making Space for Nature Project, which enhanced local green spaces for nature and people, improving local environments and access to nature. The successor Urban Green Shoots project is working to continue this improvement of community assets. (https://letstalk.cornwall.gov.uk/urban-green-shoots)\\n",
        "otherEntities": "Transport|Public authority|Climate initiatives/networks|Residents/community groups"
