        "mechanisms": "Collaborative initiative|Capacity development|Reporting of climate and/or environmental data|Knowledge or data sharing",
        "focusAreas": "Adaptation|Resilience|Emissions reduction",
        "description": "Governance, Leadership & Community - We are working with partners to ensure compliance with existing provisions and improvements for environmental protection. We commissioned a study into Environmental Enforcement in Cornwall and Isles of Scilly, which identified challenges for the sector and provided novel ideas to improve compliance. \\n\\nFindings of this report are being taken forward by the Cornwall and Isles of Scilly Environmental Enforcement Working Group which comprises representatives from Cornwall and the Isles of Scilly Inshore Fisheries Conservation Authorities, Cornwall Council, Cornwall Wildlife Trust, Devon and Cornwall Police, the Environment Agency, the Marine Management Organisation, Natural England and the National Farmers' Union. The group is considering the suggestions for improving environmental enforcement - foremost has been the need to raise awareness of how the public can report any illegal activity that is harming the environment. Production of the environmental compliance poster and web pages - https://letstalk.cornwall.gov.uk/environmental-enforcement - are the first step in a campaign to raise public awareness about the need to report environmental damage and the appropriate bodies. Future work could include new ways of working, streamlining of processes and continued focus on achieving positive environmental compliance outcomes through new mechanisms.\\n\\nCornwall Council has developed and utilises a local one planet/doughnut model Decision Wheel (Cornwall's Development and Decision Wheel) to evaluate all initiatives and projects prior to activation. https://www.cornwall.gov.uk/people-and-communities/equality-and-diversity/assessing-the-impact-of-our-decisions/ \\n\\nThe Cornwall Plan 2020-2050 was updated in 2024in line with our aspirations for environmental growth. \\n",
