      {
        "primaryEntity": "Civil society: Residents/community groups",
        "mechanisms": "Reporting of climate and/or environmental data|Knowledge or data sharing|Collaborative initiative",
        "focusAreas": "Adaptation|Natural environment|Resilience|Agriculture|Energy|Emissions reduction",
        "description": "The Cornwall Voluntary Sector Climate and Environment Alliance was formed in September 2023 and includes a diverse range of 62 (and growing) organisations from across Cornwall. These organisations work within their specific communities on various challenges such as carbon reduction, litter picking, energy, and nature recovery. The alliance also includes larger organizations like Cornwall Wildlife Trust, Surfers Against Sewage, and the Eden Project. The alliance aims to support the voluntary, community, and social enterprise (VCSE) sector in adapting, mitigating, and building resilience against climate change. In the past year, they have collected baseline data from VCSE organizations and have published a \u201cGreen Footsteps Guide\u201d for VCSE organisations, to support positive action. The Council supports and engages with the group, attending meetings, events, and sharing key information. The Council has promoted the Green Footsteps Guide through its communication channels and contributed content to the webinar series that accompanies the written report. ",
        "otherEntities": "Climate initiatives/networks"
      },
      {
        "primaryEntity": "Business: Other: Cornish businesses across a range of sectors",
        "mechanisms": "Collaborative initiative",
        "focusAreas": "Agriculture|Food|Water|Forestry|Adaptation|Energy|Education|Industry|Public health|Ecosystem restoration|Transport (Mobility)|Waste|Natural environment|Resilience|Emissions reduction|Building and Infrastructure",
        "description": "Cornwall Sustainability Awards (CSA) \\n\\nCornwall Council uses the Cornwall Sustainability Awards (CSA) to engage with residents in several impactful ways:\\n\\nCelebrating Local Efforts: The awards highlight the tireless work of community groups, charities, schools, businesses, social enterprises, and individuals in combating climate change and promoting sustainability. This recognition encourages more residents to participate in sustainable practices.\\n\\nPublic Involvement: Residents are invited to nominate projects or individuals for the awards, fostering a sense of community involvement and ownership. This inclusive approach ensures that a wide range of voices and efforts are acknowledged.\\n\\nEducational Outreach: The CSA promotes awareness and education about sustainability through various categories that address different aspects of environmental stewardship, such as tree planting, circular economy, and environmental growth. This helps residents learn about and engage in sustainable practices.\\n\\nNetworking Opportunities: The awards ceremony and related events provide a platform for residents to connect with like-minded individuals and organisations, facilitating the exchange of ideas and collaboration on sustainability projects.\\n\\nIncentivising Action: By recognising and rewarding sustainable initiatives, the CSA incentivises residents to adopt and innovate sustainable practices in their daily lives and businesses.\\n\\nThese strategies help Cornwall Council foster a culture of sustainability and community engagement across the region. \\n\\nSince CSA was launched in 2002 local Cornish businesses have been rewarded and recognised for their contribution towards sustainability, environmental growth, circular economy and carbon neutrality. Many have gone on to win national and international awards and become leaders in their field.",
        "otherEntities": "Agriculture|Energy|Residents/community groups|Utilities|NGO and associations|Health Care|Construction|Education sector|Transport|Climate initiatives/networks|Waste|Food & Beverage"
      },
      {
        "primaryEntity": "Civil society: Residents/community groups",
        "mechanisms": "Knowledge or data sharing|Collaborative initiative|Reporting of climate and/or environmental data",
        "focusAreas": "Finance|Public health|Ecosystem restoration|Natural environment|Adaptation|Energy|Agriculture|Resilience|Waste|Emissions reduction|Building and Infrastructure|Transport (Mobility)|Food|Forestry|Education",
        "description": "Cornwall Council's 'Carbon Neutral Cornwall Hive' is an online engagement platform for residents and businesses in Cornwall. The web platform provides a space for people to learn from each other and be inspired to reduce greenhouse gas emissions for better human and environmental health. It shows what the Council is doing and what other organisations and communities are leading on across Cornwall. There is a discussion forum, an ideas bank, blog posts, and sections that signpost people to useful information, resources, and funding opportunities to help get low carbon and environmental projects underway. In early 2025, a survey was sent out to gather views on the future development of the Hive and meetings with external organisations was held to hear how they use the Hive and what they think could be improved. The results of the survey and meetings are informing a refresh of the Hive platform to make it even more useful. .\\n\\nAssociated with the Carbon Neutral Cornwall Hive is the Council-led Carbon Neutral Cornwall Newsletter - https://www.cornwall.gov.uk/environment/climate-emergency/climate-emergency-news/ - that shares what is happening across Cornwall to reduce greenhouse gas emissions - for the benefit of residents and the environment. It goes out every two months and showcases what the Council is leading on as well as initiatives led by external organisations and partners. Regular correspondence and meetings with local organisations helps in deciding the content for the newsletter.\\n",
        "otherEntities": "Climate initiatives/networks|Local government within country/area"
      },
      {
        "primaryEntity": "Business: Other: Representatives from range of business sectors",
        "mechanisms": "Knowledge or data sharing|Economic development|Collaborative initiative",
        "focusAreas": "Agriculture|Other: Skills|Industry|Building and Infrastructure|Energy",
        "description": "The Cornwall and Isles of Scilly Economic Forum (the Forum) is a group led by the private sector which advises Cornwall Council and the Council of the Isles of Scilly on economic priorities to create local jobs and drive growth. Members are drawn from a wide range of sectors and include representatives of Cornwall Council, which also provides the secretariat function. The Forum was created after the Government gave more control over economic development to local areas. Its goal is to provide a strong business perspective and local expertise to support the economic growth of Cornwall and the Isles of Scilly. The Forum helps shape local economic strategies, evaluates public sector initiatives, and attracts investment to support growth and development projects. It works with the Local Authorities on strategic economic planning for Cornwall and the Isles of Scilly and the associated implementation of action and investment plans to drive sustainable and responsible economic and inclusive growth. A sub group, the Cornwall and Isles of Scilly Workforce and Skills Board, is currently developing a Workforce and Skills Strategy for Cornwall and the Isles of Scilly. \\n\\nhttps://www.cornwall.gov.uk/business-trading-and-licences/economic-development/cornwall-and-isles-of-scilly-economic-forum/\\n",
        "otherEntities": "National government|Neighboring local government|Industry trade group|Academia"
      },
      {
        "primaryEntity": "Business: Other: Businesses",
        "mechanisms": "Financing (investment)",
        "focusAreas": "Ecosystem restoration|Forestry|Natural environment|Agriculture|Finance|Adaptation",
        "description": "Launched in April 2024, the Cornwall Natural Capital Exchange Platform connects private buyers with sellers of natural capital projects. The platform currently profiles 16 high-integrity projects requiring over \u00a320 million in funding, with more in development. These projects vary in scale and outcome, ranging from thousands to millions of pounds, and include initiatives such as tree planting and river restoration. \\n\\nSo far, \u00a3100,000 of private funding has been secured for Nature Recovery Projects, and 260 Natural Capital Units (Biodiversity Net Gain) have been identified and profiled. Since its launch, the platform has received 30,000 visits and is being used as a template model by other local authorities.'\\n\\nwww.linc-cornwall.com\\n",
        "otherEntities": "Other: Landholders"
      },
      {
        "primaryEntity": "Government/Public body: Local government within country/area",
        "mechanisms": "Knowledge or data sharing",
        "focusAreas": "Emissions reduction|Energy|Building and Infrastructure|Waste|Resilience|Transport (Mobility)|Finance|Adaptation",
        "description": "Working with Town and Parish Councils. A network of larger town and parish councils' (with dedicated climate and environment / lead officers) has been established to provide support, guidance and information sharing across this tier of local government. Regular meetings are convened and a resource platform has been established to share information and case studies. The aim is to increase emission reduction via the sharing of examples and knowledge across organisations working within the same sector. ",
        "otherEntities": "Other: Town and Parish Councils only"
      },
      {
        "primaryEntity": "Civil society: NGO and associations",
        "mechanisms": "Reporting of climate and/or environmental data|Knowledge or data sharing|Collaborative initiative",
        "focusAreas": "Ecosystem restoration|Water|Natural environment|Adaptation",
        "description": "The Falmouth Seagrass Restoration Project aims to restore and protect 10 hectares of subtidal seagrass meadows within the Fal and Helford Special Area of Conservation to enhance biodiversity, carbon sequestration, and coastal resilience. In collaboration with partners including the Ocean Conservation Trust, University of Exeter, and the Falmouth Marine Conservation Group, the project involves innovative planting techniques, habitat mapping, and the establishment of voluntary no-anchor zones. The initiative supports marine biodiversity, improves water quality, and contributes to blue carbon research, with future plans focused on continued restoration, stakeholder engagement, and the development of investment models for ecosystem services.\\nhttps://letstalk.cornwall.gov.uk/falmouthseagrass\\n",
        "otherEntities": "Education sector|Other: marine sector|Academia|Residents/community groups"
      },
      {
        "primaryEntity": "Government/Public body: Public authority",
        "mechanisms": "Knowledge or data sharing|Collaborative initiative",
        "focusAreas": "Ecosystem restoration|Natural environment|Water|Other: action plan development",
        "description": "The UK Maerl Forum 2025, held on 25 April at the University of Exeter's Penryn Campus and online, was the first national event dedicated to the conservation of maerl beds\u2014rare, slow-growing coralline red algae habitats vital for marine biodiversity and carbon storage. Co-hosted by Cornwall Council and Natural England, the forum brought together researchers, marine managers, conservationists, and policymakers from across the UK, Ireland, and Brittany to align efforts, share research, and develop a strategic action plan for maerl recovery in Cornwall and beyond. Key outcomes included the formation of a steering group, identification of priority actions, and commitment to ongoing monitoring and collaboration. The forum marked a significant step toward safeguarding one of the UK's most irreplaceable marine habitats through evidence-based conservation and inclusive partnerships.\\nhttps://naturalengland.blog.gov.uk/2025/05/15/protecting-one-of-englands-rarest-marine-habitats-natural-englands-work-on-maerl/\\n",
        "otherEntities": "Academia|Residents/community groups"
      },
      {
        "primaryEntity": "Government/Public body: Public authority",
        "mechanisms": "Knowledge or data sharing|Collaborative initiative",
        "focusAreas": "Ecosystem restoration|Natural environment|Water|Adaptation",
        "description": "Cornwall Council hosts the Fal & Helford Estuary Officer who focused on protecting and enhancing the marine environment of the Fal and Helford Special Area of Conservation (SAC). The officer is responsible for designing and delivering initiatives to mitigate recreational impacts on sensitive blue carbon habitats, as outlined in the European Sites Mitigation Supplementary Planning Document. Key duties include stakeholder engagement\u2014particularly with the marine recreation sector\u2014public education, coordination of volunteer activities, and development of marine conservation materials and initiatives such as no anchor zones, and events. The role also supports delivery of the Cornwall and Isles of Scilly Marine Nature Recovery Framework and Strategy. \\nhttps://letstalk.cornwall.gov.uk/fal-helford-mpa \\n",
        "otherEntities": "Residents/community groups|Other: marine recreation sector"
      }
