        "hazard": "Biodiversity loss",
        "vulnerableGroups": "Low-income households|Marginalized/minority communities|Children and youth|Other: Biodiversity itself for habitats and species and ecosystem services they provide in terms of flood attenuation etc.",
        "sectorsExposed": "Arts, entertainment and recreation|Forestry|Human health and social work activities|Education|Conservation",
        "impacts": "The dramatic reduction in biodiversity nationally has been well-documented; changes due to climate change are more difficult to identify. However for well-studied groups (moths, dragonflies, bush-crickets & grasshoppers) the local increase in range and abundance of some species is very clear. A number of moths previously considered vagrant or rare are now common. Equally a number of species are no longer recorded or have dramatically reduced, due to a number of reasons that includes climate change. As urban development continues and populations of plants and animals are increasingly isolated losses will increase. Losses due to site management and development will continue and there will be losses due to exceptional weather (e.g. drought) and one-off events (flooding, fires).",
