    "q1_3": {
      "oversightProcesses": "Relevant departments, committees and/or subcommittees are informed by management about climate-related issues|Council (or equivalent) is informed by relevant departments, committees and/or subcommittees about climate-related issues",
      "oversightDetails": "Dartmoor National Park Authority (DNPA) was established under the provisions of the Environment Act 1995 as an independent body within the framework of local government. \\nOur role is clearly defined by Parliament through two statutory purposes to:\\n \u2022 conserve and enhance the natural beauty, wildlife and cultural heritage of the National Park\\n \u2022 promote opportunities for the understanding and enjoyment of the special qualities of the area by the public. \\nThese purposes are of equal weight unless there is an irreconcilable conflict between the two, in which case, priority is given to the first purpose to conserve and enhance the natural beauty, wildlife and cultural heritage of the National Park.\\n In pursuing the two statutory purposes, we are also required to: \\n\u2022 seek to foster the economic and social well-being of local communities within the National Park. \\nThe National Park Authority is governed by 19 Members appointed via different routes: \\n\u2022 by the Secretary of State to reflect the national interest. \\n\u2022 by constituent authorities (Devon County Council, South Hams District Council, Teignbridge District Council and West Devon Borough Council). \\n\u2022 via parish council elections and subsequent appointment by the Secretary of State.\\nIn July 2019 DNPA declared a climate and ecological emergency, the first National Park to do so. DNPA has oversight of its own operational emissions and provides a leadership role to facilitate net zero emissions across the National Park. Climate action is considered a cross-cutting theme within all strategic plans for the National Park. \\nThe Dartmoor Partnership Plan (also known as the Management Plan) is the most important document for the National Park. It sets out a vision for the National Park and objectives for the five-year period of the Plan. The Partnership Plan is developed collaboratively, with the Authority playing a crucial role in facilitating the partnership and guiding the process. The vision for Dartmoor is ambitious: it combines national and local priorities.\\nThe Vision is to make Dartmoor better for future generations: climate resilient, nature rich, beautiful, connected to the past and looking to the future; a place where people of all ages and backgrounds can live, work or visit. A place that is loved, cherished and cared for. \\n",
      "masterPlanningImpact": "Climate action has been integrated across all strategic documents for the National Park and the National Park Authority. \\n\\nVision for Dartmoor National Park 2045\\nOur Vision is to make Dartmoor better for future generations: climate resilient, nature rich, beautiful, connected to the past and looking to the future; a place where people of all ages and backgrounds can live, work or visit. A place that is loved, cherished and cared for. The Vision includes five key focuses for the future of the National Park, being Carbon Negative is one of these. \\nCarbon negative: Dartmoor's peatlands, soils and woodlands will store significantly more carbon. Responding to climate change will be embedded in our way of life, making the best use of natural resources and reducing carbon emissions.\\n\\nDartmoor Partnership Plan 2021 - 2026\\nThe Vision is delivered through the Partnership Plan. The Partnership Plan is produced on a five-year cycle and is the Plan for the place and not just the National Park Authority. The Partnership Plan is developed collaboratively and delivered in partnership. The Partnership Plan has six themes and two cross cutting themes. Climate Change is a cross-cutting theme within the Plan, recognising the role that Dartmoor can play as a carbon sink. The Plan sets out key ambitions for Climate mitigation and adaptation across Dartmoor.\\n \\nDartmoor Local Plan \\nThe Dartmoor National Park Local Plan guides what development can and cannot happen in the National Park. When planning for Dartmoor's future, the Local Plan seeks to ensure development is environmentally, socially and economically sustainable. \\n\\nDartmoor National Park Authority Business Plan 2024-2025\\nThe Business Plan is structured around the Partnership Plan, the Business Plan includes an additional priority 'to be an excellent organisation'. This priority also incorporates the net zero aims of the organisation. The Business Plan includes key actions on climate mitigation and adaptation, including peatland restoration and the production of a Climate Action Plan for the National Park to support the ambitions for the National Park to be carbon negative by 2045. \\n",
      "financialPlanningImpact": "\u2022\\tRevenue funding has been allocated for operational costs to facilitate staff working on climate actions. This includes insurance, IT and admin and financial functions \\n\u2022\\tDNPA has been allocated funds to deliver Dartmoor Headwaters\\n-working with the SW Peatland Partnership to deliver a programme of peatland restoration \\n-working with the Environment Agency and others to deliver natural flood management schemes. \\n\u2022\\tAdditional capital funding allocated to carry out repairs on Public Rights of Way \\n",
      "transitionRisks": "The resource requirements to deliver a low carbon economy are significant. This comes at a time when where there are significant financial pressures, not just for the Authority, but for all partners key to delivery of the transition. There is a risk that appropriate resources are not available to support delivery of the transition.\\nPerceptions of Climate Change across Dartmoor are likely to be mixed. DNPA and all partners will have to navigate these perceptions and engage with all communities and sectors to ensure that changes are implement in the right place, in the right way and at the right time. If communities and key stakeholders are not engaged, or if there is resistance to change the transition is likely to be delayed or complicated. \\nSome sectors in Dartmoor, such as tourism, agriculture, and small businesses, may face disruptions as they adapt to low-carbon practices. There is a risk of economic strain on local industries if the transition is not managed carefully to balance environmental goals with economic sustainability\\nA successful transition depends on supportive policy developments at both local and national levels. If policies are inconsistent or do not adequately address the local and national needs, there is a risk that the transition is not achievable. \\nAchieving net zero requires strong partnerships and collaboration across sectors. If coordination among local authorities, businesses, and other stakeholders' is not strong enough, it could lead to fragmented efforts and reduce the overall effectiveness of the transition.\\n"
    },
