        "vulnerableGroups": "Low-income households|Vulnerable health groups|Elderly|Women and girls",
        "sectorsExposed": "Real estate activities|Human health and social work activities|Water supply|Electricity, gas, steam and air conditioning supply|Transportation and storage|Sewerage, waste management and remediation activities|Waste management",
        "impacts": "According to Environment Agency data published in 2025, there are 153,617 properties in Essex considered to be at risk from surface water flooding, up from 36,000 in 2018. This equates to approx 24% of all households in Essex. This is in addition to 65,571 properties at risk of coastal and river flooding.\u2022 Increasing urbanisation with more 'grey surfaces', together with the climate impacts of changing weather patterns and heavier rain, means surface flooding would continue to increase without appropriate adaptation measures. (https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/weather/climate-change/effects-of-climate-change) \u2022 Without adaptation/mitigation, there is also a risk of closed landfill sites being affected by ground water level changes and surface water infiltrating into the waste, generating more methane gas, which makes pollution control more difficult. \u2022 Recent studies demonstrate that floods are a significant concern in agriculture, civil engineering and public health, with a range of impacts including the possibility of impact to agricultural operations, damage and disruption to infrastructure and health impacts such as drowning, injuries and hypothermia. (http://www.sayersandpartners.co.uk/uploads/6/2/0/9/6209349/sayers_2017_-_present_and_future_flood_vulnerability_risk_and_disadvantage_-_final_report_-_uploaded_05june2017_printed_-_stan.pdf ) \u2022There is growing evidence of long-term and severe impacts on mental health and wellbeing from flooding; (CCRA3-Briefing-Flooding-and-Coastal-Change.pdf) and data from the UK point to a higher probability that women report psychological distress and post-traumatic stress disorder following home flooding than men.\\' (ECC, Climate Adaptation Plan Framework, 2024) The Levelling Up Essex Strategy identifies priority places which cover both urban areas and isolated rural areas of the county, which are also exposed to flooding. These are: Tendring, Basildon housing estates, Colchester housing estates, Harlow, Rural Braintree, Canvey Island (https://www.essex.gov.uk/sites/default/files/migration_data/files/assets.ctfassets.net/knkzaf64jx5x/xTQoof74Yb8VF4DIqYGQ2/a1b9223c9730c307979a527a2270261e/Essex-County-Council-Levelling-Up-strategy.pdf).\\n",
