        "vulnerableGroups": "Children and youth|Marginalized/minority communities|Low-income households|Elderly|Outdoor workers|Vulnerable health groups",
        "sectorsExposed": "Education|Water supply|Agriculture|Waste management|Electricity, gas, steam and air conditioning supply|Human health and social work activities",
        "impacts": "Extreme summer temperatures, as seen in 2018 and 2022, cause health concerns in vulnerable people, a reduction in agricultural productivity intensified by drought conditions and put strain on infrastructure such as transport. Extreme heat days are becoming more frequent, with days exceeding the 1961-1990 average by 5\u00b0C, 8\u00b0C, and even 10\u00b0C increasing significantly. (https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/blog/2025/met-office-deep-dive-heatwaves-and-a-changing-climate)\\nThe chance of exceeding 40\u00b0C has been rapidly increasing, and it is now over 20 times more likely than it was in the 1960s. Because our climate continues to warm, we can expect the chance to keep rising. A 2025 Met Office study estimated a 50-50 chance of seeing a 40\u00b0C day again in the next 12 years. It also found that temperatures several degrees higher than we saw in July 2022 are possible in today's climate. The well-known hot summer of 1976 had more than a fortnight above 28\u00b0C, which is a key heatwave threshold in southeast England. The study finds that in today's climate such conditions could persist for a month or more. (https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/about-us/news-and-media/media-centre/weather-and-climate-news/2025/met-office-report-details-rising-likelihood-of-uk-hot-days) (https://rmets.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/wea.7741). In summer 2025, East Anglia's mean temperature was 3\u00b0C above its long-term meteorological average for June. (https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/about-us/news-and-media/media-centre/weather-and-climate-news/2025/june-2025-provisional-statistics). This follows a record-breaking spring 2025 which the Met Office described as \\'marking an unprecedented season of warmth and sunshine across the UK\\'. (https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/about-us/news-and-media/media-centre/weather-and-climate-news/2025/double-record-breaker-spring-2025-is-warmest-and-sunniest-on-uk-record)\\n\u2022 Recent extremes of weather (prolonged wet and prolonged heat) have exposed weaknesses in underlying road carriageway layers.. These are often clay sub-soils that expand and shrink, causing cracking and damage through the highway, exposing road layers to water ingress and increased deterioration. \u2022 \u2022 Recent studies indicate that extreme weather events are becoming more frequent with the poorest and most vulnerable households hardest hit. There are more than 123,000 people in Essex, including 40,000 children, living in areas that are in the 20% most deprived in the UK.\\n",
        "populationExposed": "91-100%",
