        "mechanisms": "Capacity development|Collaborative initiative|Knowledge or data sharing",
        "focusAreas": "Transport (Mobility)|Emissions reduction",
        "description": "Essex County Council Travel Planning Programme: Essex County Council's Sustainable Travel Planning Officers support the development and implementation of Travel Plans for residential, workplace, and schools, aiming to reduce single-occupancy car use and promote sustainable travel - key actions in lowering transport-related carbon emissions.\\n\\nResidential Travel Plans are Required for developments with 80+ dwellings and should include:\\n\u2022\\tTargets to reduce car use, based on census data\\n\u2022\\tMeasures to support behavioural change\\n\u2022\\tAnnual Monitoring Reports to track progress\\n\u2022\\tMonitoring Fees secured via Section 106 agreements, covering a minimum five-year period\\n\\nNew and enhanced guidance is currently being developed for large developments (1,000 dwellings+) and Garden Community sites providing a more robust process with greater links to Transport Assessments, with the aim of supporting ECC objectives in achieving better net zero carbon outcomes. \\n\\nResidential Travel Information Packs are distributed to new residents, these district-specific packs promote sustainable travel through:\\n\u2022\\thighlighting the benefits of walking/cycling \\n\u2022\\tLocal cycling routes\\n\u2022\\tBus timetables\\n\u2022\\tElectric Vehicle grants and ownership, plus car sharing info\\n\\nWorkplace Travel Plans are required for developments with 50+ employees or those impacting local transport networks. Plans aim to reduce car commuting and include:\\n\u2022\\tTargets and measures as stated above \\n\u2022\\tAccess to our Smarter Travel for Essex Network (STEN), offering free, tailored support for sustainable travel, congestion, air quality, and staff retention - we have increased participation in this group by 25% over the past few years\\n\\nSchool Travel Plans are mandatory for new/expanding schools and encouraged for all. Plans focus on pupil travel, engaging staff and parents to improve safety, health, and sustainability. ECC supports schools in creating and monitoring plans. There are currently 41 schools holding national accreditation for their Travel Plans. \\n\\nCase Study: Saffron Walden Clean Air Project All local schools achieved full accreditation by integrating active travel and anti-idling measures into their Travel Plans. The project led to measurable reductions in CO\u2082 and air pollutants, with pupils actively engaged in observing improvements.",
