    "q1_3": {
      "oversightProcesses": "Climate-related issues are considered by the government when undertaking plans and/or strategies|Climate-related issues are considered by the government when setting performance objectives|Council (or equivalent) is informed by relevant departments, committees and/or subcommittees about climate-related issues|Relevant departments, committees and/or subcommittees are informed by management about climate-related issues",
      "oversightDetails": "We work with the other National Park Authorities on the evidence base and baseline assessments of GHG emissions in the National Parks, including science based targets and trajectories for achieving net zero, carried out by Small World Consulting\\n\\nWe work with the Devon Climate Partnership and Somerset Climate Group on their respective climate action plans including a regional climate risk and vulnerability assessment\\n\\nWe work in partnership with local businesses, communities and agencies to reduce greenhouse gases and prepare for the impacts of climate change. \\n\\nWe have an organisational carbon neutral target and action plan which we report on annually \\n",
      "masterPlanningImpact": "Climate mitigation and adaptation are included as a key component of the National Park Management Plan, including a net zero target, and also the Local Plan which guide decision making on development and planning applications. They are also one of the key priorities for the Exmoor National Park Authority as reflected in its Corporate Strategy and Plan\\nThere are two climate partnerships covering the National Park, in Devon and in Somerset, which also have climate plans",
      "financialPlanningImpact": "Responding to extreme weather has a significant impact on Exmoor National Park Authority's budgeting e.g. clearing up after storm damage and repairing rights of way. ENPA has an organisational climate action plan and budgets to reduce its carbon footprint including through greening its fleet and decarbonising buildings",
      "transitionRisks": "Exmoor National Park's economy is dominated by tourism and agriculture. Both sectors are significant contributors to the National Park carbon footprint, particularly emissions from livestock farming, and travel to and from the National Park. Transitioning these sectors to a low carbon economy is a significant challenge due to remote rural nature of the National Park with very limited public transport provision and virtually no alternatives to the private car. Upland farming in a Severely Disadvantaged Area like Exmoor is very challenging financially and is generally not viable without public support. The new Environmental Land Management schemes in England provide an opportunity to help farmers transition to more sustainable and regenerative forms of agriculture.\\n "
    },
