        "primaryEntity": "Government/Public body: Other: Government funded, not-for-profit environmental organisation",
        "mechanisms": "Knowledge or data sharing|Collaborative initiative|Multi-jurisdictional regional collaboratives|Capacity development",
        "focusAreas": "Building and Infrastructure|Food|Emissions reduction|Waste|Industry",
        "description": "\u2022 Glasgow is one of eight Scottish cities that are part of the Scottish Cities Alliance (SCA) alongside the Scottish Government. The Alliance works together to promote the country's economic potential and look at ways to collective further work in relation to a series of issues including in relation to climate change and net-zero thereby ensuring that it has a wide scope across the urban landscape of Scotland/UK.\\n\u2022 GCC was formerly part of the SCA Circular Economy Working Group, and is now part of the Local Authorities Circular Economy (LACE) Working Group. The governance and delivery arrangement for the SCA's transition plan have evolved and there is no longer a requirement for the Waste & Circular Economy Working Group ('SCA Circular Economy Working Group') to meet or report back as originally intended. Rather than dissolve the group, Zero Waste Scotland asked the participants for their views on whether it should continue in some form. Following feedback and discussions, the Local Authorities Circular Economy (LACE) Working Group was established. The Working Group is chaired by ZWS and all Scottish local authorities are invited to participate. The purpose of the LACE Working Group is to support and facilitate circular economy knowledge exchange, share best practice, raise awareness on relevant national and internation research, policy, strategies and to raise awareness on collaborative opportunities between participants. \\n\u2022 In addition, Glasgow was recently awarded (May 2025) 'Mission Label' status through the Net Zero Cities Mission, joining a cohort of 100 European cities aiming to achieve net zero by 2030. Mission Label status enables Glasgow City Council to access to private finance to fund the actions identified in the Net Zero Route Map alongside expert advisory services to support increased internal resource capacity. Elements of Glasgow's submission intend to galvanise action and collaboration across Glasgow's citizens, communities, and businesses by outlining a vision for 2030 Net Zero Carbon Glasgow and providing messaging that is clear, direct, forward-looking, and compelling - serving as an invitation and catalyst for stakeholder engagement. Glasgow City Council is currently in the process of identifying how best to utilise the support now available as part of the Net Zero Cities Mission. (https://netzerocities.eu/the-netzerocities-project/)",
        "otherEntities": "Neighboring local government|Local government within country/area|Public authority"
