        "impacts": "Climate change is set to lead to heatwave conditions every summer by the middle of the century, and the Urban Heat Island effect makes the centre of London up to 4.5C warmer than rural areas surrounding the city. Higher temperatures will lead to heat-related illnesses and can exacerbate existing health conditions, including on mental health. Vulnerable populations, such as the elderly; as well as low-income and minority populations, who often reside in areas more susceptible to heat impacts, are particularly at risk. London's heatwave in July 2022 saw the highest temperatures ever recorded in excess of 40C and triggered a Level 4 national emergency, the highest level in the UK government's \\'heat-health alert system\\' indicating extreme or severe heatwave impacts expected across multiple sectors. During this period, nighttime temperatures also remained high, peaking at a high of 23.6 degrees Celsius - recent studies show that the UK is now seeing more frequent occurrences of (tropical nights) these events, particularly during heatwaves. Across the five periods of heat experienced in summer 2022 London saw 387 excess deaths from heat. The extensive and intense heat impacted vulnerable populations with multiple sectors affected, including significant house and building fires as a concurrent risk. Analyses of regional temperature-mortality relationships indicate that the threshold at which excess deaths start to increase is 24.7C, above which there is a greater rate of increase in the number of deaths per degree Celsius rise in temperatures than in other regions at a similar level. London is uniquely exposed to rising temperatures compared to the rest of the country. Its dense building stock limited green space, and high levels of surface sealing contribute to a pronounced urban heat island effect. Over half of UK homes are at risk of overheating in English homes show that specific building types are more vulnerable (Lomas et al., 2021). Flats and small dwellings (<50m2) face the highest risks. Flats are twice as likely to overheat in living rooms compared to other housing types. Bedrooms show higher overheating rates than living rooms, likely driven by poor night time ventilation, exposure to rooftop solar gain, and heat retention in top-floor rooms Projected increases in average monthly temperatures in London until 2050 show a 5-6C increase in summer and winter averages. This will have an impact on health, infrastructure and city operations.",
