        "impacts": "Currently 51,100 properties 37,359 existing homes are at high or medium risk of tidal or fluvial flooding, from the National Flood Risk Assessment data published in 2024 by the Environment Agency and 1.3 million people are living and working in areas of tidal and fluvial flood risk. Part of London (approximately 15 per cent) sits in the natural tidal floodplain. Many parts of the city nearest the river would flood on virtually every high tide, were it not for the Thames flood defences. However, the current defences were not built to withstand the higher water levels expected in the future and left unmitigated, the tidal flood risk to London will increase as sea levels rise. A 0.9 metre rise in mean tide levels is projected by 2100 over pre-industrial levels. The current flood risk to London is highest when a spring tide coincides with a North Sea tidal surge. This is caused by a specific set of meteorological conditions, including low pressure over the North Sea and a northerly wind resulting in raised sea levels. The Thames Barrier is closing more frequently now than when it was first built, as sea level affect peak high tide and surge levels. The Thames Estuary 2100 Plan outlines how to manage the risk of flooding from the Thames as sea levels rise and sea defences are aging. The Plan sets out a deadline for upgrading flood defences downstream (east) of the Thames Barrier by 2040 and upstream (west) of the Thames Barrier by 2050. The latter was recently moved forward by 15 years as a result of a review of the Thames Estuary Plan. The Plan also considers different options for upgrading the Thames Barrier itself. The recent 10-year review brought forward the deadline for a decision on this upgrade from 2050 to 2040.",
