        "focusAreas": "Waste|Water|Energy",
        "description": "Partnership working and collaboration across the heat network sector are critical for both the public and private sector to come together to support the delivery of heat networks that supply low carbon heat at a fair cost to consumers. With Heat Network Regulation and Zoning legislation introduced through the Energy Act 2023 and Secondary Legislation expected soon to deliver further detail on this. The GLA has an active collaboration with London Councils (collective of all London Boroughs and City of London) and the London Boroughs to work together to ensure a strategic approach to the development and delivery of multi-borough heat networks across London. The GLA have recently published some important reports on the opportunities represented by London's Waste Heat Sources and The River Thames (see link) to better understand the opportunity they represent and the scale of multi-borough heat networks that they could support, as an example seven strategic heat networks were identified requiring a combined investment iof around \u00a32.4bn and that could deliver around 40 million tonnes of carbon savings over 40 years. Engagement with central Government is essential for helping to influence/shape what Regulation and Zoning ultimately looks like and that has continued over the last year as they continue to define what this will look like. Engagement with other stakeholders is also happening especially around important heat loads or heat sources, for example hospital and university sites for demand and Energy Recovery Facilities and Sewage Treatment Works for heat sources, that engagement will only get more extensive and detailed as the process of Regulation and Zoning continues through secondary legislation and then implementation. The GLA and London Councils are currently running workshops with boroughs to investigate how to deliver the Zone Coordinator role in London as an essential part of the new heat network delivery mechanism. The process is continuing across London Government and evolves as information and detail around the process becomes available from government. This is will involve collaboration with a wider group of stakeholders over the coming years The London Plan also sets clear policies in relation to heat networks, to ensure that developments support them or are built ready to connect to them in the future (where appropriate). The GLA is also working with London boroughs to deliver sub-regional Local Area Energy Plans (LAEPs), three of the four have been completed and the fourth will be completed by the end of 2025 (see link), these identify the amount and type of technology and retrofit required within different parts of the city to get to net zero and enable far more efficient energy planning and effective delivery of decarbonisation activity. The next phase of the sub-regional LAEP process is the borough-level LAEP where the detail and resolution is greater again so that portfolios of specific decarbonisation projects can be identified and then taken through development and into delivery and currently 17 of the 33 London Authorities have completed or are undertaking this final phase of the LAEP process.",
