        "sector": "Stationary energy: Energy efficiency/ retrofit measures addressing existing commercial, residential and/or municipal buildings",
        "description": "The Energy Company Obligation (ECO), first introduced in 2013, is an energy efficiency scheme for Great Britain that places legal obligations on energy suppliers to deliver energy efficiency measures to domestic premises. The main objective of ECO is to reduce fuel poverty by improving the least energy efficient housing occupied by low income and vulnerable households. One route that can be used to identify these households is through Local Authority Flexible Eligibility or LA Flex. Under LA Flex, a participating Local Authority can refer owner-occupiers and private tenants that it considers to be living in fuel poverty or on a low income and vulnerable to the effects of living in a cold home. GMCA in partnership with the local authorities is delivering wave 4 of ECO. The current measures available to residents in Greater Manchester include solar panels, air source heat pumps, external wall insulation, cavity wall insulation, internal wall insulation, loft insulation, room in roof insulation and underfloor insulation. https://gmgreencity.com/eight-home-upgrades-you-could-get-fully-funded-with-eco-flex/ https://gmgreencity.com/how-new-home-energy-efficiency-funding-could-benefit-greater-manchester-residents/",
