        "hazard": "Urban flooding",
        "vulnerableGroups": "Low-income households|Elderly|Marginalized/minority communities|Children and youth|Vulnerable health groups",
        "sectorsExposed": "Construction|Human health and social work activities|Sewerage, waste management and remediation activities|Accommodation and food service activities|Real estate activities|Public administration and defence; compulsory social security|Waste management",
        "impacts": "Much of the borough lies less than five metres above sea level. The borough is particularly prone to surface-water flooding due to the limited capacity of London's Victorian sewer network, and the extent of hard surfacing in the borough. 1,500 homes in the borough are known to have flooded following extreme rainfall in July 2021. Flooding poses an immediate risk of injury and death, with greater risks to people with less adaptive capacity such as infants and those with mobility or mental health conditions. However, the main health impacts are to mental health. A UK Health Security Agency study found that those directly affected by flooding were 6 times more likely to experience mental health conditions such as PTSD, depression and anxiety. Those with existing mental health conditions or who have risk factors such as a family history of mental health conditions are at heightened risk of new or compounded mental health conditions. Greater risks are posed to those who are less likely to receive or be able to respond to flood warnings due to communication barriers; these include older people, those with language or cultural barriers, and people with mental health conditions. Flood damage to homes results in high costs for occupants. Low-income households and those who are more socially isolated, with fewer networks to draw upon, are likely to face greater difficulties both preparing for and recovering after flooding impacts. This interacts with housing tenure and type; lower-income households are more likely to rent rather than own their properties, limiting the options to invest in measures to protect the property. They may be more likely to live in basement flats which are prone to flooding. Another group severely impacted by disruption to their housing are those who have health or social care services delivered to them at home. As sewers become overwhelmed, a key infrastructure risk during surface water flooding is the surcharging of sewage above ground, including into homes, with resulting health risks. Flooding poses risks to the normal operation of any services and businesses reliant on transport as roads can become impassable, increases likelihood of potholes, and disrupts continuation of built environment and construction activities. Flooding can also disrupt non-road transport such as inundating underground stations and lines.",
        "populationExposed": "61-70%",
        "currentProbability": "Medium",
        "currentMagnitude": "Medium High",
        "futureIntensity": "Increasing",
