        "sectorsExposed": "Education|Wholesale and retail trade; repair of motor vehicles and motorcycles|Human health and social work activities|Conservation|Construction|Accommodation and food service activities|Water supply",
        "impacts": "London faces a steeply rising water deficit, projected to reach 400m litres per year by 2040. Over 25% of London's water supply is from high-risk sources, and distribution networks have an almost 25% leakage rate. When droughts emerge the impacts occur quickly, affecting health, business operations, infrastructure and amenities; the cost to London during droughts is over \u00a3330m per day. The risks are not evenly distributed, with those worst affected frequently in lower socio-economic status groups. In the instance of severe drought, supply restrictions and low water pressure may result. This can lead to a lack of water available to occupants of high rise homes and offices in particular. Occupants of these homes may be more likely to be low-income as many of the taller dwellings in the borough are social housing. Health impacts from reduced availability of water are likely to be worst among those who are more physically at risk including older people, very young children, and those with underlying health conditions. Services and business can be severely disrupted by reductions in water supply. Food and health services are particularly reliant on access to water, and services to more vulnerable groups such as education, childcare and on-site social care may be unsafe to continue without continued water access. As human needs for water are prioritised, there is likely to be die-off of planting, with impacts for local biodiversity and ecosystem services.",
