      "oversightProcesses": "Climate-related responsibilities are assigned to a committee(s) or a subcommittee(s) in the government|Relevant departments, committees and/or subcommittees are informed by management about climate-related issues",
      "oversightDetails": "The Climate Change Act (2008) made the UK the first country to establish a long-term legally binding framework to cut carbon emissions. It contains a target requiring emissions reductions by at least 100% by 2050. Hartlepool are committed to supporting the UK Government to tackle and adapt to climate change. Central government has also set out policies and proposals for decarbonising all sectors of the UK economy to meet our net zero target by 2050 in the national Net Zero Strategy: Build Back Greener. Going forward, climate change, climate adaptation and resilience, and sustainability will be better integrated into many of Hartlepool's overarching plans.",
      "masterPlanningImpact": "Hartlepool Borough Council adopted the Hartlepool Local Plan in 2018 to help guide development. As such the local authority has set out a delivery framework for the Local Plan within the Local Development Scheme. The Hartlepool Local Development Framework (HLDF) brings together and integrates policies for the use and development of land with other policies and programmes which influence the nature of places and how they function. Documents within the HLDF ensure the most efficient use of land by balancing competing demands in accordance with a clear, distinctive and realistic vision of how the area will develop and change within a demonstrable context of sustainable development The Local Development Framework comprises of documents known as Development Plan Documents (DPD`s) (which includes neighbourhood plans) and Supplementary Planning Documents (SPD`s). These form the statutory Development Plan for Hartlepool.The Borough Council has already adopted the following climate-related documents within its LDF: Green Infrastructure SPD (2014); Planning Obligations SPD (2015); Seaton Carew Regeneration SPD (2015); Tees Valley Joint Minerals & Waste DPD (2011); Transport Assessments & Travel Plans SPD (2010).As well as the DPDs and SPDs, the Hartlepool Local Plan 2018 highlights policies related to the minimising and adapting to climate change, the sustainable transport network, energy efficiency, and the natural environment and green networks.",
      "financialPlanningImpact": "This information is not known.",
      "transitionRisks": "General risks- Lack of funding- The just transition to net zero: ensuring that nobody is left behindCurrent and emerging regulation: Policy developments that attempt to constrain actions that contribute to the adverse effects of climate change or policy developments that seek to promote adaptation to climate change.- Local policies to place greater focus on climate change- The Council will publish a net zero plan for its own operations before shifting the focus to jurisdiction-wide Technology: All risks associated with technological improvements or innovations that support the transition to a lower-carbon, energy-efficient economic system. - Heavy industrial sector- Nuclear power plant approaching its decommissioning stage,- Reliance on future technologies to make the Tees Valley a Hydrogen Transport Hub, and a place for carbon capture, utilisation and sequestration Legal: All climate-related litigation claims. Market: All shifts in supply and demand for certain commodities, products, and services. - Increased demand and competition for the supplies of low-carbon and renewable technologies- International conflicts and impact on raw materials- High national inflation ratesReputation: All risks tied to changing community perceptions of a government's contribution to or detraction from the transition to a lower-carbon economy. - Lack of faith in politics- Lack of trust in Council- Low political participation- Unstable political landscape"
