        "focusAreas": "Landscape and jurisdictional approaches|Natural environment",
        "description": "\u201cCalder and Colne Landscape Links\u201d (CCaLL), is set to rejuvenate the natural environment across Kirklees and Calderdale, enhancing wildlife habitats, cutting carbon emissions, boosting flood resilience, and reducing wildfire risks. With Kirklees and Calderdale Council working in partnership, the initiative has secured substantial grant funding to embark on this transformative venture. The project has received \u00a3750,000 from the Government's Department for Environment, Food & Rural Affairs (Defra) Landscape Recovery programme and \u00a3100,000 from the Yorkshire Regional Flood and Coastal Committee. The CCaLL project aims to restore moorlands, plant trees, and create wildlife-rich habitats that better connect valley towns with moorland tops along the rivers Calder and Colne. Collaborators include the Calder and Colne Rivers Trust, Environmental Projects in Kirklees (EPIKs), Moors for the Future Partnership, and the Environment Agency. This initiative aligns with Kirklees and Calderdale's commitment to achieving net-zero carbon emissions by 2038. The project will contribute to this goal by planting trees, hedges, woodlands, and wildflower meadows, restoring peat moorlands, and creating wetlands. These natural \u201csponges\u201d will absorb carbon dioxide, enhance wildlife habitats, and mitigate climate change impacts. ",
