        "sectorsExposed": "Human health and social work activities",
        "impacts": "At a local level, climate change could result in an increase in infectious diseases. This is particularly via midges and ticks, who could spread diseases to both humans and livestock. Globally, climate change and land use change will significantly increase the risk of diseases, which could have global significance. The effects of such diseases may be detrimental to both health and economy in Newcastle, such as we have seen from Covid-19.The most vulnerable parts of the population to infectious diseases will be elderly and clinically vulnerable patients. A key focus will be on managing the impact and acute health needs on those groups in particular. The agricultural sector is particularly vulnerable as outbreaks such as those observed with bovine TB, foot and mouth disease and bird flu led to significant economic, animal welfare and mental health impacts.",
