        "focusAreas": "Energy",
        "description": "Killingworth Heat Network Detailed Project Development study was a continuation of the previous Feasibility work and was funded by the Department for Business, Energy, and Industrial Strategy (BEIS), The North East Combined authority Energy accelerator Fund. The study was delivered by Sustainable Energy Ltd. and forms a key part of the overall CO2e reduction and heating strategy for the Killingworth area.\\n\\nThe Feasibility Study and resulting Outline Business Case was concluded in December 2024 and included soft market testing with a range of UK network providers. \\n\\nThe Authority's preference is to supply the network with heat from the multiple local mines, which would celebrate the rich history of coal mining in the area. Desktop analysis of the wider coal seam concluded that sufficient yield may be available, however further investigation to confirm resource in the specific area is required. \\n\\nThrough commercial discussions during the development of the business case, it was concluded that the Council has a low-risk appetite, preferring the development of the network to be undertaken by a third party. The Council would become a key anchor load for the network and supply the developer with favourable terms for the use of the Council-owned energy centre site. Positive feedback was received from soft market testing with a number of heat network developers who were interested in the strategic location of Killingworth, and the adjoining heat network zones. \\n",
