        "sectorsExposed": "Education|Professional, scientific and technical activities|Agriculture|Conservation|Forestry|Financial and insurance activities|Water supply|Human health and social work activities",
        "impacts": "Biodiversity loss will have wide-ranging impacts across multiple sectors. In agriculture, the loss of infield trees will reduce shade for livestock, negatively affecting animal welfare and productivity. Forestry will also be impacted, as the decline of natural predators may lead to increased browsing pressure on tree crops, while a reduction in pollinators could hinder pollination and viable seed production. Water supply systems will face challenges due to stressed or degraded peatlands, which can compromise water quality and increase the need for extraction and purification for human consumption.\\n\\nConservation efforts will become more urgent as more species require protection. Climate change will drive natural migration, with native species in the park potentially shifting northward or becoming locally extinct, while new species may arrive from southern regions. These changes will disrupt food webs, species abundance, and distribution, all of which will need to adapt to the evolving climate.\\n\\nFinancial and insurance activities will also be affected, as opportunities to invest in ecological solutions may diminish and corporate social responsibility targets become harder to meet. In the realm of professional, scientific, and technical activities, research will become increasingly vital to deepen our understanding of biodiversity's role in addressing climate change.\\n\\nEducation will play a crucial role in responding to the climate and ecological crisis. Biodiversity loss will highlight the need for improved climate education to benefit future generations. Human health and social work activities are closely tied to biodiversity, as engagement with nature has proven benefits for wellbeing. This was starkly illustrated by the incident at Sycamore Gap in September 2023, which underscored the emotional and cultural importance of nature. The landscape of Northumberland National Park continues to draw people from around the world, offering a vital connection to nature that supports both physical and mental health.",
