        "impacts": "The trend of rising annual mean temperatures is projected to continue in Nottingham, posing significant challenges to the city. By the 2050s, climate models based on the RCP8.5, 90% probability level forecast the following temperature changes compared to the baseline (1981-2000).\\n\\nMean summer temperature: Increase of up to 3.7C. Mean winter temperature: Increase of up to 2.9C. Mean daily maximum summer temperature: Increase of up to 4.5C. Mean daily minimum winter temperature: Increase of up to 2.8C. Risks and Impacts The rising temperatures, particularly during summer, pose significant threats, as evidenced by events such as the Summer 2022 heatwaves. \\n\\nKey concerns include: \\n\\nBuilt Environment: Higher temperatures may lead to heat-related damage to buildings and infrastructure, impacting the city's built environment. \\n\\nTransport and Energy Supply: Increased temperatures can disrupt the Council's transport networks and energy systems, necessitating adaptations to improve resilience. \\n\\nUrban Heat Island Effect: The intensification of this effect may lead to increased cooling demands, further straining energy systems. \\n\\nPublic Health: Vulnerable groups are at heightened risk of heat-related discomfort, with potential knock-on effects for NHS services due to increased healthcare demands. \\n\\nVulnerability Assessment Emerging research (subject to change as studies progress) highlights the following: 34% of Nottingham's population has a high vulnerability to extreme heat, considering both high exposure and sensitivity to heat. \\n\\nWhen focusing solely on areas with very high heat exposure (calculated from land surface temperature) and very high sensitivity (based on seven socio-economic factors), this decreases to 1.9% of the population.",
        "populationExposed": "31-40%",
