        "impacts": "Households and businesses flooding, loss of income due to flooding and reduced transport methods. Cost of carrying out post-flooding work. There is an increased risk to all infrastructure from surface water flooding. The impact is assessed to be high as flooding is known to affect Perth and Kinross currently, and climate change is expected to increase the frequency and severity. Damage and disruption to infrastructure may have an outsize impact on rural communities. Based on flood projection data from SEPA, this is the major source of flooding in Perth and Kinross, so surface water flooding is likely to have an increased impact. Conversely, risk projections from river flooding are more mixed; railway lines and stations are more exposed, but other infrastructure such as energy and water may be less exposed. In Scotland, key infrastructure is exposed to both types of flooding. This includes water sites, power stations, and rail lines (and others). Flooding may have an impact in rural areas of Perth and Kinross, particularly in areas that are not well-connected. For example, a train line or road being flooded may have an outsize impact if that is the only major transport connection to a village. There are associated effects such as difficulties for health services in accessing remote regions if transport infrastructure is affected. Flooding can severely disrupt businesses in both the short and long term. Flooding may mandate businesses closing for repairs, and may make it difficult for them to get insurance. Flooding can damage cultural heritage such as historic buildings. It may also require attractions to be closed to the public if they require repairs.",
