        "impacts": "Risks to business from reduced employee productivity due to infrastructure disruption and higher temperatures in working environments. Risks to health and social care delivery from higher temperatures - Social Care Staff may be affected by higher summer temperatures. Buildings and equipment could also overheat. Due to the health impacts described in risk HCB8, more pressure may be placed on health care during heatwaves. Risks from summer household energy demand for summer cooling. Risks to prison services from high temperatures - Heat related illness for inmates and staff, need to move prisoners if temperatures in some areas of the prisons become too high. Only one prison in the Perth and Kinross area. Warmer / wetter winters leading to higher levels of damp and condensation in homes, which result in mould, with knock on health impacts and damage to homes. Homes most prone to this are those with poor ventilation, leaking roofs, poor plumbing and significant sources of moisture within the home. Higher summer temperatures and particularly heatwaves have an established link with premature deaths and illnesses. Heat related morbidity in the form of specific heat illness is also a problem. Heat stroke, and sunburn, dehydration are common heat induced illnesses. These can affect older and younger people and exacerbate existing illnesses such as cardio-vascular and respiratory diseases. The built environment can also play a contributory role, with urbanised areas more at risk as they retain more heat, and certain building types at greater risk of overheating. High temperatures can cause a range of detrimental effects to infrastructure networks, and cause cascading failures which affect other interlinked networks. High temperatures can cause a range of detrimental effects to transport infrastructure, such as rail buckling and road surface expansion.",
