        "impacts": "Increase in the incidence and severity of drought conditions could lead to water shortages.\\n\\nCurrent water supply infrastructure becomes overstretched and isn't resilient enough for the future.\\n\\nGround Water - Reduced opportunity for aquifer recharge ay key times of year. \\n\\nLower levels of infiltration mean that the aquifer may become depleted at times of greater demand. \\n\\nThis problem may be exacerbated by an increased demand for abstraction during the summer months.\\n\\nImpact upon the National Park area from additional water infrastructure such as pipelines and reservoirs.\\n\\nChanges in the chemical and biological status of surface waters and impacts on drinking water quality. \\n\\nDrinking water sources requiring additional treatment to meet existing quality standards in terms of chemical and biological status.\\n\\nFailure of water bodies and ground water to meet existing quality standards in terms of chemical and biological status.\\n\\nReduced precipitation and increased intensity and duration of drought may effect supply of water for agricultural use.\\n\\nReduced flows to surface waters due to drought and over-abstraction.\\n\\nGreater incidences of algal blooms and concentration of pollutants in rivers and stream due to reduced flows.\\n\\nChanges in water temperature leading to increase in occurrence and risk from invasive or harmful water-borne species.\\n\\nThreats to ecosystem and public health from pollution and microbial contamination of water.\\n\\nDisruption to water and waste water systems may require changes in infrastructure to deal with the risks to ecosystem or public health.\\n\\nReduced availability of water supply for livestock causing dehydration, heat stress and other animal welfare issues.\\n\\nNeed for supplementary water supply for livestock will mean increased capital costs and lower returns.\\n\\nInsufficient water supply to support grazing of remote or high drought prone areas and associated habitats.\\n\\n",
