        "hazard": "Coastal flooding (incl. sea level rise)",
        "vulnerableGroups": "Other: Coastal communities and those within the rural/land-based sector with land-holdings within the Heritage Coast area.",
        "sectorsExposed": "Agriculture|Arts, entertainment and recreation|Administrative and support service activities|Sewerage, waste management and remediation activities|Real estate activities|Water supply|Manufacturing|Conservation|Public administration and defence; compulsory social security|Fishing|Construction|Human health and social work activities",
        "impacts": ".\\nIncrease in incidence and severity of seasonal storm events. The SNPA has a small area of coastline (approx 13.7 Km stretch of chalk cliffs and estuary/coastal habitat and grazing marsh. It is predominantly undeveloped though there are small settlements and communities that are vulnerable to sea-level rise and impact from combined tidal and storm water surges. The main impacts are:-\\n\\nThe risk from flooding and inundation by the sea of low lying coastal areas, farm land and settlements.\\n\\nIncreased rate of erosion of coastline, coastal cliffs and dune systems from stronger storms and wave impact.\\n\\nIncreased occurrence and severity of cliff falls in areas that are vulnerable to erosion by wave impacts.\\n\\nIncreased risk of loss of heritage assets or archaeological sites from flooding or inundation by the sea.\\n\\nEnhanced or heavily engineered coastal flood defences could further impair natural functioning systems and cause knock on problems in other areas of coastline.\\n\\nInundation and flooding from more frequent storms and sea level rise may damage or disrupt water and waste management systems.\\n\\nSaltwater intrusion causing increased salinity of both surface and groundwater in coastal areas. Impact upon the quality and availability of drinking water supplies in coastal areas.\\n\\n'Coastal squeeze' - Existing land becoming inundated or being lost through coastal erosion. Increased conflict between different land uses may increase 'less space, more pressure'. \\n\\nIncreased erosion of chalk cliffs from increased in storm and wave impacts. Risk to property and farmland along the top of the chalk cliffs.\\n\\nLoss of cliff top habitats on the undeveloped coast line.\\n\\nLoss of cliff top paths and other recreational and cultural assets due to cliff falls and coastal erosion.\\n\\n\\n",
