        "refId": "Mitigation Action 24",
        "sector": "Waste: Increase awareness/engage public on waste reduction/recycling measures",
        "description": "South Tyne and Wear Waste Management Partnership Joint Municipal Waste \\nStrategy, available at https://www.sunderland.gov.uk/media/23945/WasteManagement-Strategy-2021-25/pdf/STWWPWasteManagementStrategy202125.pdf?m=637859771360670000\\nSunderland's Low Carbon Framework and the City Council's Low Carbon Action Plan aim to reduce consumption and waste including food waste - saving residents and businesses money and reducing emissions from the waste management sector.\\nStrategic Priority 7 (Consumption and Waste) aims to reduce the volume of all consumption and waste, changing what we consume and how it is produced, continuing to avoid the disposal of waste by landfill and increasing opportunities to reuse materials and recycle waste wherever possible. Moving the city up the waste hierarchy will reduce carbon emissions from the waste sector. To date, there have been several key actions which have helped to reduce emissions from the waste management sector. These include the opening of a new Household Waste and Recycling Centre with reuse facility in Pallion in 2022 and a trial (beginning in 2021) of an electric Refuse Collection Vehicle. In 24/25, 192 tonnes of waste had been diverted from EfW via the reuse shop. In 2024/25, the electric refuse collection vehicle collected 1,507 tonnes of waste, clocked 2,292 miles and completed 90,048 bin lifts. \\nThe Council's Low Carbon Action Plan continues to sharpen its focus and includes several actions to decarbonise the waste sector in Sunderland in forthcoming years.\\nThe City Council will ensure the implementation of its Zero Single Use Plastics commitment, developing and promoting initiatives to minimise plastic waste. The Council launched Refill Sunderland in 2022 to reduce single use plastic waste in the city. Refill is an award-winning behaviour change campaign led by Not-for-Profit organisation 'City to Sea' to help people live with less waste by providing a platform to connect them and their communities to places they can eat, drink and shop without single use plastic packaging. Worldwide over 480,000 people have downloaded the app and the Sunderland scheme will support businesses and consumers locally to transition towards reuse systems and tackle the global issue of plastic pollution. 130 Refill stations are currently registered within the city, with 126 offering water refills, 36 offering coffee refills and 5 offering zero waste shopping. Refill Sunderland will provide a platform for new stations to register and will help promote them. Sunderland continues to work with residents and businesses to increase the level of composting of garden waste within the city. For example https://www.mysunderland.co.uk/MowbrayCommunityGarden and https://www.sunderland.gov.uk/allotments\\nA Material Focus funding bid has been put forward by Sunderland Council to trial electrical waste collections, with the ambition to increase recycling rates of electronics.\\nA new communications piece is set to be launched early in 2026 to residents, detailing high fossil carbon items, such as textiles, and encouraging these items to be diverted to reuse and recycling centres rather than put in household waste, reducing the carbon emissions from the waste sector.\\nFollowing the introduction of the new food waste regulations in March 2025, the Council has developed a task group which has ensured all Council buildings are managing food waste effectively, as well as continuing to effectively manage recycling and waste reduction, with a bin for each being present in all buildings. \\nThe Council is also carrying out food waste collections for businesses in line with the new regulations, while also trying to encourage those outside of the regulations to opt in. As a part of the Waste Partnership, Sunderland is also collecting food waste across Gateshead, using 1 vehicle to increase efficiency and sustainability.\\nPublic Health in Sunderland are working to reduce food waste, as part of the work done by the Sunderland Good Food Partnership. Public Health colleagues are informing the development of the Adaptation Plan for Sunderland, highlighting the most vulnerable population groups to ensure the climate adaptation plan for Sunderland is informed by all known risks. https://www.sunderland.gov.uk/healthycityplan\\n",
