        "description": "Sunderland is actively seeking to facilitate investment in industrial innovation and production linked to the electrification of advanced manufacturing, reflecting the City's leading role in EV production and battery manufacturing. The primary focus for this investment is centred around the Nissan and AESC plants, the International Advanced Manufacturing Park and Hillthorn Business Park.\\nThe International Advanced Manufacturing Park (IAMP) is now part of the NE Investment Zone which was announced by UK Government in Nov 2023 focused on clean energy (offshore & renewable technologies) and green manufacturing (EV & battery production), forming part of the wider International Advanced Manufacturing Strategic Site (IAMSS). IAMP creates significant scope for large-scale production and assembly of new environmental technologies that are being developed in the area, with JATCO having announced establishment of JATCO UK at IAMP in Jan 2025 representing investment of \u00a348.7m and creation of 183 skilled jobs once fully operational to supply electrified powertrain to Nissan - in premises built speculatively by SCC to attract such investment. The IAMP is being brought forward by SCC and South Tyneside Council, with developer HBD. \\nSCC has also co-developed MADE NE, a \u00a314.6m collaborative skills and industrial innovation project focused on EV and battery manufacturing, which was approved in July 2024 as part of the NE Investment Zone with initial activity now underway. Sunderland played a key co-design role in bringing the partnership together, securing regional Investment Zone support and funding, earmarking premises and contributing to initial business development and curriculum planning. MADE NE is designed to become self-sustaining after 5 years and its Advisory Board is currently chaired by SCC. It will bring together industry, colleges and universities from across the region to create a step change in skills development for electrification and advanced manufacturing.\\nThe JATCO UK and MADE NE announcements follow earlier announcements by both Nissan and AESC. In July 2021 AESC announced that they would be building their 2nd gigaplant on IAMP with 9GWh of production capability which will create 700 jobs and safeguard a further 300 jobs. This was part of a wider announcement by Nissan regarding the creation of Nissan 36Zero in Sunderland. This inward investment announcement, which alongside JATCO UK investment will increase the city and region's green economy and support decarbonisation of transport, followed significant co-operation SCC and both Nissan and AESC as well as central government. Construction work is almost complete on site at IAMP on the new gigaplant. AESC followed this up in 2024 with a planning application as part of their feasibility study for an additional gigafactory on land adjacent to the plant under construction. In Nov 2023 Nissan announced its intention to produce 3 new models at its Sunderland plant as the company continues to transition to full electrification.\\nSunderland is home to a range of fast-growing, innovative SMEs working at the leading-edge of the electrification of the automotive and other sectors. Advanced Electric Machines (AEM) is a spin-out from Newcastle University that manufactures electric motors and drive technologies in the city. AEM employs more than 50 people in a facility with space to annually produce 12,000 next generation electric motors - and played a key role in the initial development of the Driving the Electric Revolution (DER) programme and NE Industrial Centre working with Newcastle University, the NE Automotive Alliance and SCC. The 'Driving the Electric Revolution' national programme is specifically intended to facilitate projects in the field of Power Electronics, Machines & Drives and enable the UK to capture part of the significant global market opportunity which electrification represents.\\nIn 2021, Turntide acquired Sunderland based Hyperdrive Innovation. Nurtured in the city until all operations were consolidated into their Gateshead owned facility in 2025, the company designs and produces lithium-ion battery packs and battery management systems and recently won a contract to supply Hitachi Trains to power the 1st battery powered trains in the UK. \\nThe Port has established itself as a hub for circular economy activity, with a growing cluster of businesses linked to SAF, and material recycling. The 'Trinity Rail, Road & Sea Enterprise Zone'\u2014a brownfield development site within the Port\u2014is ready for occupation and capable of supporting up to 20,000 sq.m. of low-carbon industrial floorspace, offering an Intermodal transport connectivity to reduce logistics-related emissions. Construction is progressing on a \u00a3100 million end-of-life tyre recovery facility by Norwegian company Wastefront. The facility will convert waste tyres into recovered carbon black and tyre derived oil, while creating 30+ local jobs. ",
