        "primaryEntity": "Civil society: Education sector",
        "mechanisms": "Knowledge or data sharing|Collaborative initiative|Funding (grants)|Project implementation and management|Capacity development",
        "focusAreas": "Water|Emissions reduction|Ecosystem restoration|Industry|Agriculture|Waste|Transport (Mobility)|Adaptation|Energy|Food|Education|Resilience|Forestry|Building and Infrastructure|Natural environment",
        "description": "Sunderland continues to ensure that a range of free climate-related opportunities are made available to all Sunderland schools. SCC circulate information on relevant sustainability-related climate opportunities, funding and initiatives at local, regional, national and international level. \\n \\nFor example, the Waste and Recycling Visitor Education Centre have delivered 32 waste themed sessions with Sunderland schools in the 24/25 school year. Students have taken part in part in site visits, waste crafts, litter picks, waste assemblies, waste workshops, composting and food growing workshops. \\n \\nOther carbon-cutting opportunities shared in 2024/25, include the National Education Nature Park, Let's Go Zero, Climate Ambassadors, The Ministry of Eco Education, Count Your Carbon, Climate Friendly Schools, Leadership for Sustainability Training, the Woodland Trust's Free Trees programme, Eco Schools, Keep Britian Tidy initiatives, Parkthatbike, Walk to School Week, school competitions (e.g. WWF's We Love Cities, Big Battery Hunt) and tree planting opportunities. \\n \\nLaunched during COP27 (November 2022), SCC commissioned and funded the Sunderland Climate Friendly Schools (CFS) programme, giving in-depth support to 10 primary/secondary/special schools in the city to form climate teams, undertake audits complete a whole school assembly, undergo staff training and form action plans to reach CFS status. \\nInitially led by Outdoor and Sustainability Education Specialists (OASES), the programme supports children and young people to have the knowledge, confidence and skills required to drive the city's low carbon ambitions forward. \\nKepier, St Anthony's Girls Catholic Academy, Portland Academy, Albany Village Primary School, Barmston Village Primary School, Barnes Junior School, Hetton Lyons Primary School, Hudson Road Primary School, Seaburn Dene Primary School and Wessington Primary School took part in the CFS project and received intensive support to develop their curriculum and make climate-friendly changes from 2022-2024. \\n \\nSchool actions are based around 7 climate themes including energy, transport, building, water, food, consumption, and grounds. Climate actions schools have delivered include developing schools gardens, introducing plants into the classroom, teaching children about future green careers, promoting uniform/ costume swap shops, installing a water butt to harvest rainwater, energy saving school switch off, investigating renewable technologies, food waste programmes, and planting trees. \\n \\nAll 10 CFS Schools have attained CFS status for 2 years of activities, working towards year 3. \\n \\nAlongside CFS, 5 other Sunderland schools (St Aidan's Catholic Academy, Harry Watts Academy, Ryhope Junior School and St Benet's RC Primary School) supported the development of a Wear Sustainable resources toolkit, including lesson plans for all key stages, loans box and trails. These are free and accessible to Sunderland schools. \\n \\nFollowing successful engagement with the first 10 Sunderland CFS, SCC committed to embedding the programme by funding a new cohort of 5 schools to take part in CFS from September 2024, whilst supporting the first cohort to achieve the year 3 award. This has included drawing down school support from Sunderland's Low Carbon Lead Teachers (Associate School Improvement Advisors), supporting their professional development. \\n \\nDiamond Hall Infant Academy, Benedict Biscop CE Academy, Southmoor Academy and North View Academy have taken part in the project this year. \\n \\nAlongside this, SCC has continued to run and grow the Sunderland Climate Friendly Schools Network through a mixture of online and in person sessions, cascading free resources and opportunities to all schools, as well as providing a space for schools to share best practice. \\n \\nThis year, SCC has worked with Together for Children to embed climate change education and action within the Sunderland Healthy Schools Award, which has seen the development and launch of the Sunderland Low Carbon Charter Mark. This Charter is one of six Charter Marks within the Sunderland Healthy Schools Award. The Charter Mark is a tool for implementing sustainable practices into school life, from curriculum changes to community outreach and giving young people the tools they need to build a greener future. Several schools have already expressed an interest in getting involved. \\n \\nThe Charter was officially launched in June 2025, at the Sunderland School Climate Conference, featuring 'Sunny Bee', a climate-conscious mascot inspired by children's artwork submitted at last year's conference and chosen by the Environmental, Green and Sustainable Group. \\n \\n22 Sunderland schools attended the second annual conference, where pupils took part in climate-themed activities, best practice sharing and networking with climate education organisations. 105 Pupils and 35 members of Teaching Staff attended the conference, along with 12 Organisations",
