        "refId": null,
        "sector": "Transportation: Improve rail, metro, and tram infrastructure, services and operations",
        "description": "The WMCA has secured over \u00a32.4 billion to expand the regions tram, train, bus and cycle networks as part of wider efforts to decarbonise transport in the region. This funding is from the Government's City Region Sustainable Transport Settlement (CRSTS). This funding is going towards improving metro expansion, train network expansion, expanding cycle networks and improving bus services (all detailed elsewhere). For example, one project included in the CRSTS settlement is for the delivery of 1,000 electric vehicle charging points and 10 ultra-rapid charging stations at key locations for commercial fleets at a cost of 48 million. The WMCA has also received a 15.7 million boost (from the Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure Fund) to its plans to install up to 12,000 electric vehicle chargers across the region over the next five years. Transport for West Midlands (TfWM) is investing a total of 6.1 billion to deliver a green transport revolution across the region, expanding Metro, bus, rail, cycling and walking networks over 15 years, up to 2032: https://www.wmca.org.uk/news/6-1-billion-investment-is-delivering-a-green-transport-revolution-to-regenerate-the-west-midlands/ \\n\\nThe West Midlands became the first Future Transport Zone which resulted in an excellent programme of delivery in innovation- including: a mobility credits trial which has explored incentives to move people away from private motoring, the launch of an app-based demand responsive bus service and the development of the real world test bed for connected and autonomous vehicles. The region is also leading the way in developing and testing Very Light Rail technology (VLR) which will make tram systems more affordable and quicker to deploy, making mass rapid transit more easily attainable for towns and cities. The VLR technology has had 72 million earmarked to develop, with some of this investment going towards a real world demonstration track in Coventry city centre- in 2025 a 220 meter test section of track was installed with a successful pilot period with over 2000 local residents riding the VLR in the pilot period. \\n\\nFollowing the Trailblazer Devolution Deal secured in 2023, the WMCA area will become the UK's first Transport Sandbox- this designation gives us the opportunity to work in partnership with central government to flex and challenge existing legislation to help us deliver better transport services for our residents and businesses. TfWM will be working with government, local authorities and wider industry and academic partners to: Enable new, low speed zero emission and automated vehicle trials, looking at both operational and regulatory challenges; Explore the flexibility of current rules and regulations to allow new dynamic responsive models of bus services. This builds on the recent West Midlands On Demand/Ring and Ride merger and the automated passenger vehicle trials being undertaken at Birmingham Airport, Solihull: Accelerate dynamic traffic management and digitisation of street spaces, supporting last mile logistics and creating safer streets and places. The Sandbox forms a part of the region's Local Transport Plan- called Reimagining Transport in the West Midlands- which sets out the aim of providing safe, convenient and affordable transport services and infrastructure so that local amenities are within a 15-minute trip by walking, wheeling, cycling or scooting, and regional facilities and workplaces within 45 minutes journey by public or shared transport. The plan recognises that car milage must reduce to meet net zero by 2041. The plan outlines it's key themes as 'six Big Moves', and the WMCA Board will launch a further round of public engagement on the six Big Moves:1) Behaviour change 2) Accessible and inclusive places 3) Safe, efficient and reliable network 4) Walk, wheel, cycle and scoot 5) Public transport and shared mobility 6) Green transport revolution.\\n\\nThe WMCA also secured 4 million from the Government in 2023 to create a UK Centre for Excellence in Road Decarbonisation, known as The UK CO2llaboration Centre of Excellence for Materials Decarbonisation. The centre will bring together technical expertise from around the world to develop and trial new innovations that will accelerate the use of low carbon materials, and repair and maintenance techniques. These could include road surfaces made from recycled components or materials such as permeable concrete to improve their durability in different climates, to studying the carbon impact of pothole repair techniques based on costs and long-term lifespan. The centre will work closely with TfWM's established Transport Skills Academy to share the knowledge and skills developed so it contributes to the academy's work to upskill the region's existing highways and transportation workforce. In 2025 this work has continued to progress, with live trials of new and innovative road materials are taking place in the West Midlands - including Coventry, Dudley, Sandwell, and Walsall.\\n",
