        "engagementPurpose": "The development of this component is required by the national government (e.g., by law, regulation and/or agreement)",
        "comment": "The National Park Management Plan is a statutory plan that involves a partnership between the National Park Authority and local partners, such as local government, and departments of central government (e.g. Historic England, Forestry Commission, Forestry England, Natural England). The Plan is renewed every 5 years with the current plan effective from 2025-2030 (note: the plan has been adopted by members but is currently awaiting publication). \\n\\nBy 2040 the National Park will be resilient and responsive to the impacts of climate change, storing more carbon each year than it produces. \\nThe Plan contains Ambitions (with each Ambition having associated objectives to achieve that Ambition) that relate to Climate mitigation and adaption. Mitigation objectives are:\\n\\nB1: Work with farmers and landowners to support food production through the use of regenerative farming practices, working with natural processes, across at least 100 farm holdings (c15,000 ha) by 2030.\\n\\nB3: Work with farmers and landowners to encourage creation of 6,000 ha of native broadleaf and mixed woodland, including, scrub, wood pasture and natural regeneration by 2031, to create a network that increase resilience to climate change and reduce downstream flood peaks.\\n\\nB5: Support more services along the Settle-Carlisle Railway and the reinstatement of other rail lines, increase bus and shared transport links to surrounding towns, and improve infrastructure for electric vehicles, so as to reduce greenhouse gas emissions from travel by 50% by 2030 (compared to 2019).\\n\\nB6: Support initiatives to improve the energy efficiency of buildings and increase small\\u0002scale and community renewable energy schemes, so as to reduce energy costs and reduce greenhouse gas emissions from industrial, commercial and domestic properties by 50% by 2030 (compared to 2019).\\n\\nD1: Support farmers and land managers to maintain and improve the outstanding landscape, geology, wildlife and heritage of the National Park, so that at least 80% of land managers have adopted nature-friendly farming or land management on at least 15% of their land by 2030.\\n\\nD2: Maintain the National Park as a place where a true sense of tranquillity and remoteness can still be found, including taking action to retain international 'Dark Sky Reserve' status\\n\\nD5: Support farmers and landowners to enhance the Dales' landscape, and support nature, climate and farming resilience, including planting field trees to mitigate the impact of ash dieback on tree cover outside woodlands, , and creating or restoring 60 km of hedgerows by 2030 (from 2022 baseline).\\n\\nE1: Establish an integrated National Park farm advisory service to: support regenerative farming; increase take-up of national agri-environment schemes and green finance opportunities; and, so support the viability and retention of low input livestock farming across the National Park.\\n\\nE2: Provide advice, training and support for rural and land-based businesses to help them to innovate, diversify, and secure investment in their natural assets and create 'green jobs', so as to retain at least the same number of jobs within the sector. \\n\\nE3: By 2030 provide at least 30 apprenticeships or traineeships, and wider programmes of training in land management, heritage and green skills, including the new skills needed by businesses to support more nature-friendly farming and tackle climate change.\\n\\nF6: Produce local plans to improve connections for walking, cycling, wheeling and horse-riding, so it is easier for residents and visitors to travel for work, for school and to access key services and visitor destinations without needing a car, and create at least 2 new multi-use routes by 2030, including one linking Garsdale-Hawes. "
