        "comment": "The National Park Management Plan is a statutory plan that involves a partnership between the National Park Authority and local partners, such as local government, and departments of central government (e.g. Historic England, Forestry Commission, Forestry England, Natural England). The Plan is renewed every 5 years with the current plan effective from 2025-2030 (note: the plan has been adopted by members but is currently awaiting publication). \\n\\nBy 2040 the National Park will be resilient and responsive to the impacts of climate change, storing more carbon each year than it produces. The Plan contains Ambitions (with each Ambition having associated objectives to achieve that Ambition) that relate to Climate mitigation and adaption. Adaption objectives are: \\n\\nA1: Improve the condition of protected wildlife sites so that 60% of features in Sites of Special Scientific Interest are assessed as having 'actions on track' to achieve favourable condition by the start of 2028, and at least 45% are in favourable condition by 2030. \\n\\nA2: Support farmers and landowners to restore and manage landscape-scale mosaics of semi-natural habitats in 6 'nature recovery areas' ('Cumbria Connect'; 'Heart of the Dales'; 'Snaizeholme'; 'Tees-Swale'; 'Three Dales'; and 'Ure Dales'), and develop similar initiatives for at least 3 additional areas. \\n\\nA3: Increase the area of priority habitat outside of Sites of Special Scientific Interest that is in favourable management through agri-environment or similar funding schemes by 10,000 ha by 2030. \\n\\nA4: Ensure that recovery plans are in place and being implemented for all 'priority wildlife species' by 2030, so that 85% of those species have stable or increasing populations by 2035. \\n\\nA5: Work with farmers, landowners and water companies to improve the condition of rivers - including significantly reducing the frequency of spills from storm overflows at 10 sewage treatment works - so that 65% are in 'good ecological status' by 2031. \\n\\nA7: Support farmers and landowners to restore or create 5,000 hectares of new wildlife-rich habitats outside protected sites by 2030 (from a 2022 baseline). \\n\\nA8: Support farmers and landowners to bring 75% of woodland into sustainable management by 2030, including positive management of conifer plantations to increase habitat for red squirrels and black grouse \\n\\nB2: Work with farmers and landowners to bring all remaining degraded peatland (c28,000 ha) into initial restoration and management by 2035. \\n\\nB4: Significantly increase take up of natural flood management measures to reduce flood risks inside and outside the National Park, including 're-naturalising' 25 km of watercourses by 2030"
